<section>
    <h2>Strong Passwords</h2>
    <img src="https://example.com/strong-password.jpg" alt="Strong Password Image">
    <p>A strong password is made up of at least 16 characters and contains upper and lower case letters, numbers, and symbols. Strong passwords also follow best practices, avoiding personal information, dictionary words, and never being reused across multiple accounts. (Trevino, 2023)</p>
    <p>Learn more about creating secure passwords on <a href="https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/top-tips-for-staying-secure-online" target="_blank">NCSC's website</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Identify Safe and Unsafe Sites</h2>
    <img src="https://example.com/website-security.jpg" alt="Website Security Image">
    <p>Website owners are responsible for visitor safety, but some websites can spread malware or steal information. Here are three ways to identify a safe site:</p>
    <ul> 
        <li><strong>Look for HTTPS:</strong> Sites with "HTTPS" use encryption. Sites with only "HTTP" may be unsafe.</li>
        <li><strong>Check for a Privacy Policy:</strong> A legitimate site has a clear privacy policy about data handling.</li>
        <li><strong>Find Contact Information:</strong> Trustworthy sites provide contact info. A survey showed 44% of users avoid sites without it (SiteLock, 2024).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For more information on identifying secure sites, visit <a href="https://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/how-recognize-and-avoid-phishing-scams" target="_blank">FTC's Guide</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Malicious Software (Malware)</h2>
    <img src="https://example.com/malware.jpg" alt="Malware Image">
    <p>Malware is harmful software that infects devices or networks. Its effects can range from minor issues to severe damage, depending on its type and purpose. (Yasar, n.d.)</p>
    <p>Read more about malware types and protection at <a href="https://us.norton.com/internetsecurity-malware-what-is-malware.html" target="_blank">Norton Security</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Cyber Scams</h2>
    <img src="https://example.com/cyber-scam.jpg" alt="Cyber Scams Image">
    <p>Cyber scams are crimes where criminals deceive victims to steal money or information. Cybercriminals often impersonate trusted figures, contacting victims via email, social media, or other sites. (Trevino, 2023)</p>
    <p>Learn more about how to avoid cyber scams at <a href="https://www.fbi.gov/how-we-can-help-you/safety-resources/scams-and-safety/common-scams-and-crimes/internet-fraud" target="_blank">FBI's Internet Fraud Page</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
    <h2>Phishing</h2>
    <img src="https://example.com/phishing.jpg" alt="Phishing Image">
    <p>Phishing is a form of cyber scam where criminals trick victims into providing personal information, often by pretending to be trusted contacts. (Trevino, 2023)</p>
    <p>Visit <a href="https://www.phishing.org/what-is-phishing" target="_blank">Phishing.org</a> to understand phishing and how to protect yourself.</p>
</section>

